values.description:
* Model submison for X4 sensor config 3 from ssci. Added 360 rgbd camera.
* Minor revisions to comply with formatting and reduce clutter.

Added a ring of 6 rgbd cameras for 360 fov. \(topic names camera\_1,…,camera\_6\)

Added point lasers above and below as in previous PRs \(topic names top\_scan, bottom\_scan\)

We did not add lights for the 360 degree view because we are interested in the depth data, but lights can be added later. We did not add visual geometry for the new cameras, but we did adjust the mass of the vehicle to account for the additional cameras.

Originally submitted as ssci\_x4\_sensor\_config\_9

values.description:
The number of lights were reduced to 8 from 19 for performance reasons.

changes are:

* removed 2 spot lights from the front
* removed 2 spot lights from the back
* removed all 7 LED point lights
* removed visuals that are marked as fully transparent
* enable cast\_shadows on the remaining 8 spot lights \(this is expensive, hence the need for reducing number of lights\)

The visuals marked as transparent were likely used by the led / flash light plugin in gazebo classic. Since the plugin is not ported, these visuals are not used so I removed them. Same for the LED point lights. We don’t have the plugin to turn them on and make them blink so I removed them for now.

Here’s a screenshot:

![](data/bitbucket.org/repo/8ze6Mjd/images/1320809788-explorer_x1_8_lights.png)
‌

‌

values.description:
This uses the new velocity controller added in [ign-gazebo PR 487](https://bitbucket.org/ignitionrobotics/ign-gazebo/pull-requests/487/). I have only updated X3C5 and X4C6 for now and would like some feedback on the noise characteristics of the two vehicles. With the new controller, the `<ROBOT_NAME>/cmd_vel` topic is actually a velocity topic and can be used to control the linear velocity and the yaw angle velocity of the vehicle. Note that the velocity commands are expressed in the body frame of the vehicle.

The update also exposes a topic `<ROBOT_NAME>/velocity_controller/enable` which can be used to enable/disable the controller. The controller is enabled by default but waits for the first command on the `cmd_vel` topic to do anything. Publishing a `false` would disable the controller and would cause the vehicle to fall.

## To test
First, build ign-gazebo with the PR 487 branch. 

Then launch 

values.title: Use the new multicopter velocity controller for UAVs

summary.raw:
This uses the new velocity controller added in [ign-gazebo PR 487](https://bitbucket.org/ignitionrobotics/ign-gazebo/pull-requests/487/). I have only updated X3C5 and X4C6 for now and would like some feedback on the noise characteristics of the two vehicles. With the new controller, the `<ROBOT_NAME>/cmd_vel` topic is actually a velocity topic and can be used to control the linear velocity and the yaw angle velocity of the vehicle. Note that the velocity commands are expressed in the body frame of the vehicle.

The update also exposes a topic `<ROBOT_NAME>/velocity_controller/enable` which can be used to enable/disable the controller. The controller is enabled by default but waits for the first command on the `cmd_vel` topic to do anything. Publishing a `false` would disable the controller and would cause the vehicle to fall.

## To test
First, build ign-gazebo with the PR 487 branch. 

Then launch 
```
ign launch -v 4 urban_circuit.ign robotName1:=R1 robotConfig1:=X3_SENSOR_CONFIG_5  robotName2:=R2 robotConfig2:=X4_SENSOR_CONFIG_6 
```
And publish velocity commands
```
rostopic pub /R1/cmd_vel geometry_msgs/Twist "{x: 0.0, z: 0.1}" "{}"
```

```
rostopic pub /R2/cmd_vel geometry_msgs/Twist "{x: 0.0, z: 0.1}" "{}"
```

To hover, publish
```
rostopic pub /R1/cmd_vel geometry_msgs/Twist "{}" "{}"
```

values.description:
This makes the artifact validator use the world SDF file. This will mean that all artifacts are visible without having to iterate through levels to find them at the cost of having another copy of the SDF file in memory somewhere.

As a future enhancement for Gazebo, we can store the spawned SDF in the EntityComponentManager somewhere to keep from having to do this workaround.

This also adds two new services: `prev` and `move_to` which allow you to move backwards or jump to a particular artifact.

As a future enhancement for Gazebo, we can store the spawned SDF in the EntityComponentManager somewhere to keep from having to do this workaround.

This also adds two new services: `prev` and `move_to` which allow you to move backwards or jump to a particular artifact.

values.description:
This is an utility for running some checks over a SubT log file. Right now, it can be used for checking if any object is below a certain height.

How do I use it?

1. Compile and run SubT to generate a log file.
2. Run the log checker. Here’s an example:

```
./install/lib/subt_ign/log_checker --file=/tmp/ign/logs/state.tlog --topic=/world/urban_circuit_practice_01/dynamic_pose/info --minz=0
```

Make sure to update the path to your log file, the world name in your topic, and the minimum Z value.

1. As a human, you can see the verbose output generated by the program. E.g.:

```
******************************
Configuration:
  Log file: [/tmp/ign/logs/state.tlog]
  Topic name: [/world/urban_circuit_practice_01/dynamic_pose/info]
  Minimum Z: [0]
Output report:
  Minimum Z check: [true]
******************************
```

Programmatically, you can also check the exit code of the program:

```
echo $?
0
```

where the exit code means:

`0`: All checks have passed.

`1`: The checker is not correctly initialized. E.g.: Incorrect path or topic, missing minZ argument.

`2`: Unable to playback the log file. Unlikely unless there’s some internal error in the player.

`3`: At least one check hasn’t passed.

values.description:
Each team submitted robot configuration defines its own `spawner` method so when multiple team submitted robots are requested, the `spawner` method collides and the incorrect method canbe called, e.g. this causes ign launch to fail:

```
ign launch -v 4 urban_circuit.ign circuit:=urban worldName:=simple_urban_02 robotName1:=X3 robotConfig1:=X3_SENSOR_CONFIG_5 robotName2:=X4 robotConfig2:=X4_SENSOR_CONFIG_6 robotName3:=X5 robotConfig3:=X3_SENSOR_CONFIG_5
```

I’m not an expert in ruby but it seems like doing a `load` instead of `require` makes sure that the last loaded `spawner` method is used.

Also fixed a ruby warning about `UAVStr` being a constant variable \(variables that start with capital letter is treated as a constant\).
